{
  "answer": "**Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 75** defines bride-price (*śulka*) as follows: \"Whatever value is received for household utensils, vehicles, milch animals, ornaments, and servants, that is declared to be the bride-price (*śulka*). // K_898 //\".[^1]\n\n**Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 76** caps the gift of a woman's separate property (*strīdhana*) by relatives at two thousand while explicitly forbidding immovable property: \"*Strīdhana* should be given to a woman by her father, mother, husband, brother, and kinsmen, according to their ability, up to two thousand, but not immovable property. // K_902 //\".[^2]\n\n[^1]: [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/75/translation/#p-9e5207).\n\n[^2]: [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/76/translation/#p-f86392).",
